For a two-dimensional electron gas (2DEG) representing only the Shockley surface-state band with two-dimensional electron density $n^{2D}$ determined from the surface-state Fermi energy $E_{F}^{2D}=2.8\\,$eV and with effective mass $m^{*}=m_{e}$ (the free-electron mass), the conventional long-wavelength 2D plasmon dispersion is
      $\\omega_{2D}(q)=\\sqrt{\\dfrac{2\\pi n^{2D}e^{2}}{m_{e}}\\,q}$;
      using these values for $n^{2D}$ and $m^{*}=m_{e}$, the isolated-surface-state 2D plasmon energy at $q=0.05\\,a_{0}^{-1}$ evaluates to approximately $\\hbar\\omega_{2D}\\approx 2.7\\,$eV, and this estimate represents the plasmon energy of the isolated surface-state band under the stated effective-mass assumption.
